          <div class="section-heading">
            <p class="eyebrow">Why septic maintenance matters</p>
            <h2>What happens when septic systems are neglected</h2>
            <p>Most septic failures trace back to two things: a tank that has gone too long between cleanings and drains that have never been properly maintained. Understanding the consequences helps prioritize regular service.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="trust-stack">
            <article><span>01</span><div><h3>Leach field failure</h3><p>When the tank overflows with solids, they migrate into the leach field and clog the drain lines and surrounding soil. Replacing a leach field costs thousands of dollars and disrupts the entire yard.</p></div></article>
            <article><span>02</span><div><h3>Sewage backups into the home</h3><p>A full tank cannot accept incoming wastewater. The sewage backs up through the lowest fixtures in the home — floor drains, basement toilets, and tubs.</p></div></article>
            <article><span>03</span><div><h3>Sewage surfacing in the yard</h3><p>When the leach field is saturated or the tank is overflowing, raw sewage surfaces in the yard — a health hazard and environmental violation.</p></div></article>
            <article><span>04</span><div><h3>Foul odors inside and outside</h3><p>A system that is not processing waste properly releases hydrogen sulfide and other gases through fixtures, vents, and the leach field area.</p></div></article>
            <article><span>05</span><div><h3>Contaminated groundwater</h3><p>A failing septic system can contaminate wells and nearby water sources with bacteria, nitrates, and other harmful pollutants.</p></div></article>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

