            <p class="eyebrow">Warning signs</p>
            <h2>Signs your septic system needs service</h2>
            <p>Watch for these indicators that your septic system needs professional attention before a small problem becomes a major expense.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="callout-list">
            <div><strong>Slow drains across the entire home</strong><span>When multiple fixtures drain slowly, the tank may be near capacity and unable to accept incoming wastewater.</span></div>
            <div><strong>Septic alarm sounding</strong><span>The high-water alarm indicates the tank level has reached a critical point and service is urgently needed.</span></div>
            <div><strong>Wet or soggy area over the leach field</strong><span>The leach field is saturated — either the tank is overflowing solids or the field itself is failing.</span></div>
            <div><strong>Sewage odors in the home or yard</strong><span>Gases escaping from an overloaded system create persistent, unpleasant smells near fixtures and outside.</span></div>
            <div><strong>Unusually green or lush grass over the leach field</strong><span>Nutrient-rich sewage reaching the surface feeds the grass above the drain field — a sign of system stress.</span></div>
            <div><strong>More than 3 years since last cleaning</strong><span>Most residential systems need pumping every 3 to 5 years depending on tank size and household use.</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

