            <p class="eyebrow">How it works</p>
            <h2>How your septic system works</h2>
            <p>Understanding the basics of your septic system helps you recognize problems early and maintain it effectively.</p>
            <ul class="check-list">
              <li><strong>Inlet:</strong> Wastewater flows from the home through the inlet line into the septic tank</li>
              <li><strong>Tank:</strong> Solids settle to the bottom and are slowly digested by bacteria. Grease and oils float to the top as scum.</li>
              <li><strong>Outlet:</strong> Clarified liquid (effluent) flows from the tank into the leach field through the outlet baffle</li>
              <li><strong>Leach field:</strong> Effluent percolates through gravel and soil, where natural bacteria complete the treatment process</li>
            </ul>
            <p>When the tank is not cleaned on schedule, solids accumulate past the outlet baffle and flow into the leach field — clogging it permanently.</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <p class="eyebrow">Cleaning frequency</p>
            <h2>How often should your septic tank be cleaned?</h2>
            <p>The right cleaning schedule depends on your specific system and household.</p>
            <ul class="check-list">
              <li><strong>1-2 person household:</strong> Every 4 to 5 years for a standard 1,000-gallon tank</li>
              <li><strong>3-4 person household:</strong> Every 2 to 3 years for a standard 1,000-gallon tank</li>
              <li><strong>5+ person household:</strong> Every 1 to 2 years, or more frequently with heavy use</li>
              <li><strong>Garbage disposal users:</strong> Reduce interval by 1 year — disposals add significant solids to the tank</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Honest Drain recommends a schedule based on your actual tank size, household size, and use patterns — not a one-size-fits-all number.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

